---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<BaseLayout
  title="The 2018-2022 mandate · Riksdag Revealed"
  description="Sweden's 2018-2022 Riksdag mandate read with the chamber record, the eight 2018 election manifestos and the parties' parliamentary reasoning. Three coalition arrangements, one four-year mandate."
>
  <article class="container">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="byline">Riksdag Revealed · The 2018-22 mandate</p>
      <h1>Three coalitions, one mandate</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Sweden's 2018-2022 Riksdag mandate, read on its own terms.
        The article uses chamber votes, written reservations, and the
        eight 2018 election manifestos as evidence. Cross-mandate
        comparisons sit on the
        <a href={`${base}/`}>longitudinal overview</a>; this page is a
        self-contained reading of the previous mandate.
      </p>
    </header>

    <p>
      The 2018 election produced a Riksdag with no parliamentary
      majority for either of the two traditional blocs. After four
      months of negotiations, the Löfven II cabinet was formed by
      Socialdemokraterna and Miljöpartiet on the basis of the
      January Agreement, a written deal with Centerpartiet and
      Liberalerna that exchanged confidence-and-supply support for
      a set of policy commitments. Moderaterna, Kristdemokraterna
      and Sverigedemokraterna were the opposition for most of the
      mandate. Liberalerna left the January Agreement in 2021;
      Miljöpartiet left the cabinet in 2021. The Magdalena Andersson
      cabinet replaced Löfven II in late 2021. The mandate ended
      with the September 2022 election.
    </p>

    <p>
      This was therefore not a single-government mandate, and the
      cabinet support structure changed substantively during the
      four-year window. The figures below average over the whole
      mandate unless explicitly broken down by riksmöte. Where
      year-by-year structure matters, it is shown separately.
    </p>

    <h2>The chamber map</h2>

    <p>
      Every chamber vote of the mandate, member by member,
      projected into two dimensions through PCA on the
      444-by-3,203 vote matrix.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/60_chamber_map_18_22.png`} alt="The 2018-22 chamber map" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        PCA on the 2018-22 vote matrix. Each dot is a Member of
        Parliament; the labelled circles are party centroids. PC1
        and PC2 capture the two largest axes of variance in MP
        voting behaviour over the four-year mandate.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Three structural features stand out. Sverigedemokraterna sits
      on its own arm of PC2 near +15, far from any other party on
      the second axis. Moderaterna and Kristdemokraterna are below
      the origin on PC2 and to the left on PC1, in the bottom-left
      quadrant; Liberalerna and Centerpartiet sit close together
      between them and the origin. The red-green grouping (S, V,
      MP) clusters tightly on the upper-right of PC1, consistent
      with S and MP sharing a cabinet for most of the mandate.
    </p>

    <h2>The January Agreement in the chamber data</h2>

    <p>
      The January Agreement (Januariöverenskommelsen) was signed in
      January 2019 between Socialdemokraterna, Miljöpartiet,
      Centerpartiet and Liberalerna. Under the agreement, C and L
      abstained on the confidence vote that allowed the Löfven II
      cabinet to form, in exchange for 73 written policy
      commitments. The agreement formally ended in June 2021 when
      Liberalerna withdrew, and the cabinet composition changed
      again in November 2021 when Miljöpartiet left and
      Socialdemokraterna formed a single-party government under
      Magdalena Andersson. The chamber data shows how each of these
      transitions affected voting patterns.
    </p>

    <p>
      Centerpartiet's per-year vote correlation with
      Socialdemokraterna moved from -0.06 in 2018-19 (before the
      agreement was signed) to +0.08 in 2019-20 and +0.17 in
      2020-21 (the two full years of the agreement). The same
      pattern applies to the MP-C correlation. Centerpartiet's
      votes became measurably more aligned with the cabinet's votes
      during the years the agreement was in effect.
    </p>

    <p>
      Liberalerna's per-year vote correlation with
      Socialdemokraterna did not move in the same way. S-L
      correlation was -0.06 in 2018-19, near zero throughout
      2019-21 (between 0.00 and -0.05), and -0.15 in 2021-22 after
      L withdrew. Liberalerna was less integrated with the cabinet
      on the chamber record than Centerpartiet was, even during
      the years L was formally a support party. The asymmetry
      between the two support parties shows up cleanly in the
      vote-correlation data.
    </p>

    <p>
      The S-MP per-year correlation, which had sat at 0.99 across
      the first three riksmöten of the mandate (Socialdemokraterna
      and Miljöpartiet shared a cabinet, so they voted as one),
      fell to 0.63 in 2021-22 after Miljöpartiet left in November
      2021. This is one of the few cabinet transitions in the
      chamber data of this period and shows that the change in
      government composition registered immediately in the
      parties' voting alignment.
    </p>

    <h2>Where parties disagree most, 2018-22</h2>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/56_per_topic_stance_18_22.png`} alt="Per-topic vote stance, 2018-22, top 20 polarising topics" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Mean vote stance per (party, unified topic), top 20 topics
        by cross-party variance. +1 means the party consistently
        voted Yes on points classified into that topic, -1
        consistently No, 0 mixed. Topics sorted left-to-right by
        cross-party variance.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Most party-topic cells sit in positive territory: the
      majority of contested chamber votes in 2018-22 passed, and
      most parties voted Yes most of the time on those points. The
      main exceptions are Sverigedemokraterna's distinctive
      positions on rights and disability questions, where SD's mean
      stance is markedly more negative than the other parties'. On
      most other topics the parties cluster broadly into a
      red-green grouping (S, V, MP) close to the cabinet, an
      Alliance-leaning group (M, KD), the two centre parties (L,
      C) in the middle, and Sverigedemokraterna at the edge.
    </p>

    <h2>Vote versus reasoning</h2>

    <p>
      For every party pair we measured a vote-stance similarity
      from the chamber record and a reasoning similarity from
      topic-centred cosine between reservation reasoning vectors.
      In 2018-22 the reservation coverage is full (every party has
      reservation material in at least 26 of 28 topics), so no
      speech-based fallback is needed.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/58_vote_vs_reasoning_18_22.png`} alt="Vote-versus-reasoning scatter, 2018-22" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Each point is one party pair. The dashed line is the
        cross-pair trend. Highlighted pairs: S-MP (the Löfven
        cabinet partners); KD-M (Alliance partners); M-SD (vote
        alike at 0.92 and reasoning at moderate similarity).
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Three pairs are worth naming. S-MP sit at the highest vote
      similarity (0.94) and the highest reasoning similarity (0.60)
      of any pair, consistent with their cabinet partnership through
      most of the mandate. KD-M sit at 0.95 vote and 0.37
      reasoning, consistent with their Alliance partnership and
      shared opposition vocabulary. M-SD vote at 0.92 with
      reasoning at 0.31, above the cross-pair trend, indicating
      that the two parties' parliamentary reasoning vocabularies
      sat closer together than their vote pattern alone would
      predict.
    </p>

    <p>
      The most below-trend pairs in 2018-22 are S-L, V-M, MP-L,
      MP-KD and V-KD. These are pairs where the parties voted
      together on a substantial share of contested votes (typically
      because both supported or both opposed the cabinet's
      legislation) but their reservation reasoning texts diverge
      sharply.
    </p>

    <h2>Top behavioural defectors</h2>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/61_defectors_18_22.png`} alt="Top 12 behavioural defectors, 2018-22" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The 12 Members of Parliament with the highest
        distance-to-own-party-centroid relative to
        distance-to-nearest-other-party. Each label gives the MP's
        modal party and the nearest-other-party in parentheses. A
        ratio above 1 means the MP voted closer to another party
        than to their own.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The 2018-22 list is dominated by Vänsterpartiet members
      (Gudrun Nordborg, Jonas Sjöstedt, Hillevi Larsson) and a
      group of Socialdemokrat MPs whose voting records sit closer
      to Miljöpartiet than to S. The S-MP defectors are six MPs
      (Ida Karkiainen, Patrik Engström, Anna-Caren Sätherberg,
      Helene Hellmark Knutsson, Ingemar Nilsson and others) whose
      vote patterns reflect the shared red-green agenda of the
      cabinet partnership.
    </p>

    <p>
      Two Centerpartiet MPs (Abir Al-Sahlani and Hanna Wagenius)
      sit closer to Liberalerna than to their own party, which is
      consistent with the C-L closeness already visible on the
      chamber map. The pattern is one of within-party variation
      across what was a centre-positioned group, not a
      caucus-wide drift toward a single other party.
    </p>

    <h2>The 2018 manifestos</h2>

    <p>
      Re-classifying the eight 2018 election manifestos with the
      same three-element keyword pools (diagnosis, end state,
      mechanism) gives the per-party register shares of the
      mandate's electoral material. The numbers below describe
      the manifestos as documents in their own right.
    </p>

    <p>
      Three parties were notably diagnosis-heavy in 2018:
      Vänsterpartiet at 10.3 percent of substantive sentences,
      Moderaterna at 10.1 percent, and Centerpartiet at 9.6
      percent. These were the three parties whose manifestos
      spent the most space describing what was wrong with
      Sweden as they saw it. The least diagnosis-heavy was
      Miljöpartiet at 3.3 percent.
    </p>

    <p>
      Miljöpartiet and Socialdemokraterna were the most
      end-state-heavy manifestos at 13.7 and 12.2 percent. Both
      parties were in the cabinet at the time and both wrote
      vision-heavy documents that led with what Sweden should be.
      The least end-state-heavy in 2018 was Moderaterna at 6.0
      percent.
    </p>

    <p>
      The most mechanism-heavy 2018 manifestos were Miljöpartiet
      (18.4 percent), Sverigedemokraterna (18.2 percent), and
      Socialdemokraterna (18.0 percent). These three parties had
      the largest share of policy-instrument language (verbs like
      <em>höja</em>, <em>skärpa</em>, <em>reformera</em>,
      <em>införa</em>) of the eight. Vänsterpartiet, with 6.8
      percent mechanism, sat at the other end: more diagnostic,
      less instrumental.
    </p>

    <p>
      Length varied substantially: Kristdemokraterna's manifesto
      was the shortest of the eight at around 1,750 substantive
      words, while Sverigedemokraterna's was the longest at
      13,400 words. Direct cross-party comparisons of the
      register shares should account for the fact that a 1,700-word
      manifesto and a 13,000-word manifesto are different
      documents, and the keyword pools may capture different
      proportions of substance from each.
    </p>

    <h2>Stated and revealed, 2018-22</h2>

    <p>
      Using the same topic-matched methodology applied throughout
      the project, we embedded each 2018 manifesto sentence into
      the same vector space as the 2018-22 reservation reasoning,
      assigned each sentence to its nearest unified topic, and
      computed the within-(party, topic) cosine between manifesto
      mean and reservation mean. Per-party mean across covered
      topics:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>SD: 0.70 mean across 15 topics.</strong> The
      highest topic-matched similarity in the 2018-22 set.
      Sverigedemokraterna's 2018 manifesto and its 2018-22
      reservations describe policy in compatible language across
      the broadest range of topics.</li>
      <li><strong>M: 0.68 across 13 topics.</strong> Moderaterna's
      2018 manifesto and reservation reasoning sit in a similar
      register on the topics where both have substantive
      coverage.</li>
      <li><strong>V: 0.68 across 10 topics.</strong>
      Vänsterpartiet's 2018 manifesto and its 2018-22
      reservations describe their topics in close to the same
      vocabulary.</li>
      <li><strong>MP: 0.65, KD: 0.66, L: 0.66, C: 0.63,
      S: 0.63.</strong> The remaining parties fall in a narrow
      0.63 to 0.66 band.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The spread between parties is small. From 0.63 to 0.70 is
      a 7-percentage-point range; the eight parties' manifestos
      describe their parliamentary records relatively uniformly
      well in this mandate. Sverigedemokraterna's place at the
      top of the ranking reflects both a long, technical manifesto
      and a long record of detailed reservation work in a
      compatible register.
    </p>

    <h2>Reservations as a structural signal</h2>

    <p>
      Reservations are dissenting opinions filed by opposition
      parties on committee reports. Their count per (party, year)
      is a direct indicator of the party's role in the chamber
      that year. In 2018-22 all four of Moderaterna,
      Kristdemokraterna, Liberalerna and Sverigedemokraterna
      filed several hundred reservations per year, consistent
      with their opposition role. Vänsterpartiet also filed
      several hundred per year despite being a sometime
      negotiating partner of the cabinet. Centerpartiet's count
      rose during the January Agreement period as the party
      took a more active reservation-filing role.
      Socialdemokraterna and Miljöpartiet filed under 300 per
      year during the Löfven II cabinet, rising in 2021-22 as
      the cabinet composition changed.
    </p>

    <p>
      Sverigedemokraterna was the heaviest reservation-filer of
      the eight in 2018-22, with between 697 and 1,093
      reservations per year (peaking in 2021-22). The party's
      output on the formal opposition record of this mandate was
      among the largest of any party in any single mandate in
      the dataset.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <p class="method-note">
      Source data and methodology are documented on the
      <a href={`${base}/method`}>method page</a>. Cross-mandate
      comparisons sit on the
      <a href={`${base}/`}>longitudinal overview</a>. The 2018
      manifestos are from the SND "Vi vill" archive; the chamber
      data is from
      <a href="https://data.riksdagen.se">data.riksdagen.se</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .method-note {
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    color: var(--ink-muted, #555);
  }
</style>
